text.tspan: High-Level vision
- make platform engineering a 1st class citizen for the whole org
- invert the direction: all changes (ALL), flow in one direction only
- DEV -> test -> ci/cd
current practice is often: set up production, then "backport" production to an environment called "dev", "testing",
etc
- the SDLC is integrated: the infrastructure, your application, they are promoted together
- "always" use the most up-to-date software, conscious decision: a promise to keep the systems up to date
- no vendor-specific DSL, using a real, general-purpose language; current: python, future: more
- hard rule: the IDE guides you in meaningful ways how to write the code through auto-complete
- minicluster is the foundation, and people develop specific clusters on top (much like Docker, but for clusters of
machines)
- production is constructed with the help of minicluster, not in parallel: it's not possible to upgrade or manipulate
production otherwise
- GOAL: make an ecosystem, build the hype (conferences, articles, etc)
Motivation
- help organizations make their "initial commit" already with many guardrails in place
- processes, pipelines, etc, easy to define and to tweak
- magic: make it feel like magic starting a new project
- no magic: while still maitaining full control (knowledge) over how this are set up
Current problems in practice:
- the "dev environment" is identical only by trust, not by guardrails
- customer wants an MVP and setting up the infrastructure is not a priority, is not budgeted
- using all the "cool tools" gives an initial speedup in setting things up, but long-term all development is even more slowed down
-- cause: too much magic, too little fostering of knowledge/discovery and learning

text.inkscape:label: how to help
text.tspan: How to help
- Generally: help does not mean just writing code, it also means testing, writing/improving documentation, reporting problems
- other help possible in the future, but too early for now:
-- promoting the project, finding new contributors
-- introducing it in your own projects or companies
-- develop your own minicluster layouts and features: enriching the ecosystem
Necessary:
- make working on your machine: build base artifacts, while documenting the steps and fixing or reporting any problems/showstoppers
Next:
- let's organize more intensive meetings in the next weeks
- understand the code
- go through the TODOs, some are really easy, others are quite easy
- beware: we don't have a release, not even 0.0.1, so things are really shaky
- BEST: discuss with me if you want to do something; very often ideas are not bad, but the timing is not good, and best is to do some things later
QUESTIONS! IDEAS?
